goals.question: What is the trend of unemployment rate over the years?
goals.visualization: Line chart of unemployment rate against year
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify if there is a general increase or decrease in unemployment rate over the years.

goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployment rate across different states?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of unemployment rate against state
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify which states have higher or lower unemployment rates.

goals.question: What is the relationship between unemployment rate and education level?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of unemployment rate against education level
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify if there is a correlation between education level and unemployment rate.

goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployment rate by gender?
goals.visualization: Stacked bar chart of unemployment rate against gender
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify if there is a difference in unemployment rate between genders.

goals.question: What is the trend of unemployment rate for different age groups?
goals.visualization: Line chart of unemployment rate against age group
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify if there is a difference in unemployment rate between age groups and if there is a trend over time.

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['Unemployment_Rate'])]
    plt.plot(data['Year'], data['Unemployment_Rate'], color='blue')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('What is the trend of unemployment rate over the years?')
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('unemployment.tsv', delimiter='\t')
chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
```

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.style.use('ggplot')
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.bar(data['State'], data['Unemployment Rate'], color='blue')
    plt.xlabel('State')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unemployment rate across different states?')
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('unemployment.tsv', delimiter='\t')
chart = plot(data)
```

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y')
    plt.scatter(data['Education'], data['Unemployment'], c=data['Year'], cmap='viridis')
    plt.colorbar(label='Year')
    plt.xlabel('Education Level')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('What is the relationship between unemployment rate and education level?')
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('unemployment.tsv', delimiter='\t')
chart = plot(data)
plt.show()
```

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y')
    data = data.set_index('Year')
    data = data[['Men', 'Women']]
    ax = data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6), rot=0)
    ax.set_xlabel('Year')
    ax.set_ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of unemployment rate by gender?')
    ax.axhline(y=data['Men'].mean(), color='blue', linestyle='--', label='Men Mean')
    ax.axhline(y=data['Women'].mean(), color='orange', linestyle='--', label='Women Mean')
    ax.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y')
    data = data.set_index('Year')
    age_groups = ['16-19', '20-24', '25-34', '35-44', '45-54', '55-64', '65+']
    for age_group in age_groups:
        plt.plot(data.index, data[age_group], label=age_group)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('What is the trend of unemployment rate for different age groups?')
    plt.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```
